\begin_layout Paragraph*
Space Division Multiple Access (SDMA): 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This technique makes use of spreading tags over the reading area.
 It provides a high increase in the reading efficiency 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SDMA"

\end_inset

.
 The main drawback is the cost of implementing the RFID reader with multiple
 antennas.
 Moreover, in dense applications, the distances between the tags is very
 small to be distributed on the reading area.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Code Division Multiple Access (CDMA): 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This protocol uses spread-spectrum modulation techniques to transmit the
 data over the entire spectrum
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "CDMA"

\end_inset

.
 CDMA is the ideal procedure for many applications, e.g.
 navigation systems.
 However in case of RFID systems, it is not compatible with EPCglobal C1
 G2 , as the cost of the tags will be dramatically increased.
 Thereby, it is not a sufficient protocol for dense RFID networks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Time Division Multiple Access (TDMA): 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this protocol, a single frequency band is divided to time slots and is
 assigned to tags.
 One of the most important features of this technique is that each tag must
 be synchronized to the time slots and send its information at the beginning
 of the selected slot 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "TDMA"

\end_inset

.
 This technique can be directly applied to passive RFID systems.
 In such systems, the simplicity of tags transfers the complexity to the
 readers, where the reader has to control the time synchronization.
 However, in active RFID systems, synchronization can be either centralized
 or distributed to the tags.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In UHF passive dense RFID system, both TDMA and SDMA are the most commonly
 used PHY-layer anti-collision protocols.
 In these systems, there is only a single reader versus a large number of
 tags.
 Thus, there is no problem to increase the complexity of the reader.
 However, the tags should be as cheap and simple as possible.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
MAC-Layer Anti-collision Protocols
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unfortunately, the physical layer anti-collision proposals are not cost
 effective for the market challenges of the passive RFID technologies.
 Therefore, collision solutions are commonly implemented at the MAC layer.
 This section will discuss the most common MAC-layer anti-collision protocols.
\end_layout

